## Angular displacement

The [angle of rotation](/Angle) from the black ray to the green segment is 60°, from the black ray to the blue segment is 210°, and from the green to the blue segment is 210° − 60° = 150°. A complete rotation about the center point is equal to 1 [tr](/Turn_(geometry)), 360[°](/Degree_(angle)), or 2[π](/Pi) [radians](/Radian).

Angular displacement, often denoted by the symbols θ, ϑ, or φ, is precisely what it sounds like: the measurement of an angle through which a [physical body](/Physical_body) has executed a [rotation](/Rotation). It quantifies how much a body has revolved or spun around a designated center or [axis of rotation](/Axis_of_rotation). While seemingly straightforward, this concept underpins much of [rotational kinematics](/Kinematics). The units employed for expressing this displacement are typically [radians](/Radian), [degrees](/Degree_(angle)), or [turns](/Turn_(geometry)), each offering a different scale for the same fundamental quantity. What makes angular displacement particularly useful, and occasionally a source of minor inconvenience for those who prefer simple magnitude, is that it can be *signed*. This sign indicates the *sense* of the rotation—for instance, distinguishing between a [clockwise](/Clockwise) movement and a counter-clockwise one. Moreover, the absolute value of angular displacement isn't constrained to a single [turn](/Turn_(angle)); a body can rotate multiple times, accumulating a displacement far greater than 360° or 2[π](/Pi) [radians](/Radian).

### Other names
rotational displacement, angle of rotation

### Common symbols
θ , ϑ , φ

### [SI unit](/SI_unit)
[radian](/Radian), [degree](/Degrees_(angle)), [turn](/Turn_(unit)), etc. (any [angular unit](/Angular_unit))

### In [SI base units](/SI_base_unit)
[radian](/Radian) (rad)

